WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.960
I'm going to be talking about exploratory programming in Quarto with MBDev.

00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:13.200
Just a little bit about myself.

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:17.120
I've been a data scientist for about 15 years.

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:21.639
About half of that I've been building machine learning infrastructure and tools for data

00:00:21.639 --> 00:00:23.920
scientists and software engineers.

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:27.920
Worked at places like DataRobot, Airbnb, GitHub.

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:31.559
Somewhere along the way I met somebody named Jeremy Howard.

00:00:31.559 --> 00:00:36.119
You might know him from his popular course on machine learning.

00:00:36.119 --> 00:00:37.119
It's called Fast AI.

00:00:37.119 --> 00:00:43.240
He also has a library by the same name.

00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:48.480
Most recently I've been working on a project from Fast AI called MBDev.

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:56.020
It's something that Jeremy used as kind of a secret weapon for his personal productivity

00:00:56.020 --> 00:01:02.020
and something that I find completely fascinating and it's really something very profound that

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:04.699
I want to share with you today.

00:01:04.699 --> 00:01:06.639
So what is this talk about?

00:01:06.639 --> 00:01:12.860
So in this talk I'm going to be introducing MBDev and MBDev and some associated tools

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:22.379
kind of compose like a dialect of Python and these tools allow me and other developers

00:01:22.699 --> 00:01:26.059
to be very productive.

00:01:26.059 --> 00:01:34.620
And this dialect of Python focuses on Python's dynamic properties and really focuses on REPL

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:40.980
driven development so that you can build software with kind of this REPL driven development

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:43.339
and software engineering in mind.

00:01:43.339 --> 00:01:47.660
So the reason I'm saying that is I really want you to keep an open mind to new workflows

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:51.820
and new IDs and new conventions of ways of doing things that you may not necessarily

00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:53.980
be used to when you're seeing Python.

00:01:53.980 --> 00:01:59.300
And all of this is supercharged by Quarto, which I'll talk about as well.

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:05.339
So just to set the foundation, I think a lot of people can agree like in scientific computing

00:02:05.339 --> 00:02:10.660
but also in software engineering in general, exploratory programming is very critical to

00:02:10.660 --> 00:02:12.160
our workflows.

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:19.220
So at least in kind of the Python community this is very kind of a source of tension.

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:24.259
So this is a screenshot from Joel Grew's I Don't Like Notebooks talk, if you may have

00:02:24.259 --> 00:02:26.899
seen it.

00:02:26.899 --> 00:02:33.259
And Joel Grew also spends a lot of time in the iPython show and he goes back and forth

00:02:33.259 --> 00:02:35.779
between VS Code and iPython.

00:02:35.779 --> 00:02:43.500
And kind of it's a, this kind of is a, the debate of what tools to use and whether to

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:49.779
use notebooks or not are very indicative of this tension that people feel in their

00:02:49.779 --> 00:02:50.779
tooling.

00:02:50.779 --> 00:02:54.580
They want to use exploratory programming but they encounter a lot of friction when they

00:02:54.580 --> 00:02:55.580
have to go back and forth.

00:02:55.580 --> 00:03:00.339
You have to live in almost two worlds, the exploratory world and then the world of your

00:03:00.339 --> 00:03:09.619
text like static environment, which is a text editor, which is really painful.

00:03:09.619 --> 00:03:18.500
RStudio I feel like knew this from the beginning and I started off as R, as an R programmer.

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:24.220
And I feel like some of this knowledge was baked into RStudio.

00:03:24.220 --> 00:03:30.100
So I don't think in this audience anything I'm saying is controversial.

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:34.380
Another kind of unrelated observation.

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:39.779
So other than sort of REPL-driven development and exploratory programming, we also have

00:03:39.779 --> 00:03:41.899
amazing tools to document code.

00:03:41.899 --> 00:03:48.660
Things like R Markdown and Jupyter notebooks where we can weave together code and prose.

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:54.220
However, the interesting observation is, at least for Python, this is not being leveraged

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:57.419
to its full potential for documenting code.

00:03:57.419 --> 00:04:03.619
At least in Python land, a lot of people are, you know, copying and pasting code into Markdown.

00:04:03.619 --> 00:04:07.500
In this case, what I'm showing here on the screen is scikit-learn documentation and we

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:13.660
have code being copied and pasted into doc strings and outputs of code in doc strings,

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:14.660
which is not ideal.

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:21.019
You're copying and pasting code into a kind of static environment and that's very painful.

00:04:21.019 --> 00:04:25.859
So the question is, is there something we can do about this?

00:04:25.859 --> 00:04:28.820
Can we have the best of both worlds?

00:04:28.820 --> 00:04:33.940
And the answer to that is mbdev is something like that.

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:38.700
So mbdev brings everything together into one interface.

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:45.220
Exploratory programming, documentation, even things like testing, continuous integration,

00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:47.820
and also Python packaging.

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:51.940
So I was so excited when I experienced mbdev.

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:55.380
I've been using it for almost three years.

00:04:56.380 --> 00:05:00.420
And, you know, I felt like it was kind of this iPhone moment to me where, like, all

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:08.019
of a sudden this technology was all bundled into one thing and it was very productive.

00:05:08.019 --> 00:05:14.299
So just to give you an idea of what mbdev is, let me do just a little bit of live coding,

00:05:14.299 --> 00:05:19.980
which I try not to do at talks, but we will see how it goes.

00:05:19.980 --> 00:05:25.220
So what I'm going to do here is, I don't know if you can see this, let me zoom in a little

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:26.220
bit.

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:28.339
On the right-hand side is a notebook.

00:05:28.339 --> 00:05:33.059
And what I'm going to do is I'm going to just author a very simple Python module that's

00:05:33.059 --> 00:05:37.179
a playing card, like a deck of cards playing card.

00:05:37.179 --> 00:05:40.339
And the idea is, I'm going to show you just a little bit about mbdev, just to whet your

00:05:40.339 --> 00:05:41.779
appetite.

00:05:41.779 --> 00:05:43.540
So at the top of the notebook you have this directive.

00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:46.859
It's very much like a quarto directive, as you can see.

00:05:46.859 --> 00:05:53.859
And this default export, default exp, tells what Python module this notebook is going

00:05:53.859 --> 00:05:57.700
to be compiled to.

00:05:57.700 --> 00:06:00.459
And then the corresponding source code is on the left.

00:06:00.459 --> 00:06:03.859
You see this is card.py, which corresponds to card.

00:06:03.859 --> 00:06:09.739
And then we have some pros in the notebook, and then we have some snippet of code.

00:06:09.739 --> 00:06:13.380
This export just signifies that this is source code.

00:06:13.380 --> 00:06:25.980
So I'm going to go ahead and kind of do this fast version of kind of pretending like I'm

00:06:25.980 --> 00:06:26.980
authoring code.

00:06:26.980 --> 00:06:35.500
So I'm going to create this card class, and I'm going to export this code.

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:38.980
I'll go through it in a little bit.

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:42.619
Just for brevity purposes, I kind of created this code beforehand, so you don't have to

00:06:42.619 --> 00:06:46.660
sit here and watch me code, because that's not the point of the presentation.

00:06:46.660 --> 00:06:50.299
But basically just imagine you're writing some code in a notebook.

00:06:50.299 --> 00:06:51.660
Some of it is source code.

00:06:51.660 --> 00:06:55.420
So I create this, I have this code here.

00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:58.220
I have some card.

00:06:58.220 --> 00:07:04.459
Actually this here might be something I want to, and you might want to have some pros.

00:07:04.459 --> 00:07:11.540
So for example, you can create a card like this.

00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:12.619
Very simple.

00:07:12.619 --> 00:07:15.980
And then you might want to show the representation of that card.

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:16.980
So this is a three of diamonds.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:17.980
It's kind of small.

00:07:17.980 --> 00:07:19.940
I don't know whether you can see it or not.

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:23.820
And then you can go into other things such as, you know, let's just write some more pros

00:07:23.820 --> 00:07:24.820
here.

00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:37.859
So let's do a markdown cell and say you can compare cards like so.

00:07:37.859 --> 00:07:50.660
And then I might want to do something like create another card and maybe, you know, compare

00:07:50.660 --> 00:07:51.660
it.

00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:55.980
So let's just say this should be bigger than that, so it's true.

00:07:55.980 --> 00:07:58.380
And then, you know, I might want this to be a test.

00:07:58.380 --> 00:08:03.739
So I might want to put a test here and say, hey, this should be true.

00:08:03.739 --> 00:08:08.380
And then actually maybe here I might want another test, but I might want to hide this

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:09.500
test.

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:17.660
So I might want to say, okay, I want to make sure that this, you know, this is represented

00:08:17.660 --> 00:08:18.660
the right way.

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:19.859
And I might want to go ahead and hide that.

00:08:19.859 --> 00:08:25.700
I'm going to put the hide directive here, okay?

00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:28.059
And that's kind of very simple.

00:08:28.059 --> 00:08:32.859
Now what I'm going to do is I'm going to do export, mbdev export, and what we have is

00:08:32.979 --> 00:08:39.099
you see the source code has been generated in the Python module from the notebook.

00:08:39.099 --> 00:08:42.580
So you can think of notebook as syntactic sugar for source code.

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:47.020
But then also at the same time, what we have is you have tests.

00:08:47.020 --> 00:08:53.340
So I can run mbdev test here, console, and then you'll see it will go through and test

00:08:53.340 --> 00:08:54.340
all the notebooks.

00:08:54.340 --> 00:08:57.539
Now, nothing failed, but let's say something does fail, so I'm going to make that an equal

00:08:57.539 --> 00:08:58.539
sign.

00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:05.419
And you'll see that you see a failure message and it will show you, hey, in this notebook

00:09:05.419 --> 00:09:08.940
there's a failure, okay?

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:11.140
So great.

00:09:11.140 --> 00:09:16.460
And then the next thing I want to show you is the documentation.

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:23.299
So let me make this screen a little bit bigger so you can kind of see it.

00:09:23.299 --> 00:09:25.099
And so the documentation looks like this.

00:09:25.099 --> 00:09:28.020
This is generated by Quarto as well.

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:31.780
You have this very simple documentation that shows you the example, shows you the test,

00:09:31.780 --> 00:09:34.659
hides cells that you might not want to see.

00:09:34.659 --> 00:09:35.659
And so that's the gist of it.

00:09:35.659 --> 00:09:42.859
That's kind of whetting your appetite, just scratching the surface of what mbdev is for.

00:09:42.859 --> 00:09:49.020
So kind of to summarize, so let's go back to the slides.

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:53.099
So when you create this notebook, that's when the magic starts.

00:09:53.099 --> 00:09:54.739
That's just the beginning.

00:09:54.739 --> 00:10:01.260
So at that point where you create this code, the first thing you get is Python modules,

00:10:01.260 --> 00:10:02.859
which you saw.

00:10:02.859 --> 00:10:04.900
You can do actually a two-way sync between them.

00:10:04.900 --> 00:10:12.179
So you can make edits in the plain text version of that and it syncs backwards for quick edits.

00:10:12.179 --> 00:10:16.859
And you can navigate with your plain text editor if you like things like C tags and

00:10:16.859 --> 00:10:20.500
things like that.

00:10:20.500 --> 00:10:23.739
You can develop Python modules from notebooks very easily.

00:10:23.739 --> 00:10:30.380
So you can import things, work very similar semantically to how you would author modules

00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:31.900
in general.

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:34.460
The documentation gets rendered with Quarto.

00:10:34.460 --> 00:10:42.859
The readme can even be generated with a notebook, which is really cool.

00:10:42.859 --> 00:10:45.700
And then tests are also done for you.

00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:53.820
So you can write unit tests in your notebook, and mbdev comes kind of prepackaged with everything

00:10:53.820 --> 00:10:55.479
you need to do CI.

00:10:55.479 --> 00:11:00.340
So when you create an mbdev project on GitHub, it comes with everything you need already

00:11:00.340 --> 00:11:04.940
prebundled, the CI is already turned on, your tests are already running.

00:11:04.940 --> 00:11:12.179
And similarly, with the Quarto documentation, the machinery to host this on GitHub pages

00:11:12.179 --> 00:11:13.179
is already turned on.

00:11:13.299 --> 00:11:16.700
So all you do is create your project, you get a live site with your documentation site,

00:11:16.700 --> 00:11:20.700
you get CI if that's what you choose.

00:11:20.700 --> 00:11:22.700
And then you also get Python packaging.

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:27.299
mbdev takes care of all the boilerplate, a lot of the boilerplate involved with Python

00:11:27.299 --> 00:11:29.460
packaging, and it can be really significant.

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:34.140
So things like PyPy and Conda, it takes care of that as well.

00:11:34.140 --> 00:11:41.219
So the thing that's really powerful is usually when you're done writing code, what do you

00:11:41.219 --> 00:11:42.219
do?

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:47.380
And sometimes you might create documentation, maybe another effort.

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:50.219
You might figure out, okay, how am I going to package this?

00:11:50.219 --> 00:11:52.179
And that's a different effort.

00:11:52.179 --> 00:11:56.859
And then similarly, you might think about, okay, I need to set up my CI, I need to do

00:11:56.859 --> 00:12:01.820
all of these things, and also maybe clean up your tests.

00:12:01.820 --> 00:12:04.340
But all of this comes for free.

00:12:04.340 --> 00:12:06.539
And the thing is, it's all in one context.

00:12:06.539 --> 00:12:09.780
You're not switching context all the time for all these different things.

00:12:09.780 --> 00:12:12.020
You're writing software this way.

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:17.219
And I want to say that we've written all kinds of different software with mbdev.

00:12:17.219 --> 00:12:22.619
It's not just scientific computing libraries like fast.ai, but it's also terminal user

00:12:22.619 --> 00:12:24.859
interfaces, API clients.

00:12:24.859 --> 00:12:29.780
There's a Python client for the GitHub API called ghapi.

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:32.820
It's also written in mbdev.

00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:35.179
We've written all kinds of other infrastructure.

00:12:35.179 --> 00:12:40.260
So a wide range of software has been built with this.

00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:46.380
So it is quite robust.

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:51.419
And as I mentioned, you can think of notebooks kind of as syntactic sugar for source code.

00:12:51.419 --> 00:12:54.940
So this is a comment from Eric who works at Lyft.

00:12:54.940 --> 00:13:01.900
He uses this in production at Lyft, and he says, I can write docs, test, and code all

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:02.900
in one place.

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:08.179
And he also says, I get a lot of skeptical looks when I say the source code is notebooks,

00:13:08.179 --> 00:13:10.299
but that's just syntactic sugar for raw source code.

00:13:10.299 --> 00:13:17.419
So I mean, he really, really understands kind of mbdev in that way.

00:13:17.419 --> 00:13:22.020
And really, so another thing, if you want to kind of experience mbdev and try it, which

00:13:22.020 --> 00:13:29.460
I encourage everybody to do, one kind of useful mindset is to kind of realize it's a dialect

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:30.460
of Python.

00:13:30.460 --> 00:13:32.539
This is not just programming in notebooks.

00:13:32.539 --> 00:13:39.739
There's also a lot of extensions to the Python programming language that complement mbdev.

00:13:39.739 --> 00:13:45.380
There's a library called fastcore, which is also, not surprisingly, built in mbdev, which

00:13:45.380 --> 00:13:49.900
makes it easier to program in a notebook.

00:13:49.900 --> 00:13:55.700
Things like it makes sure that tab completion works even better for things, and it makes

00:13:55.700 --> 00:14:02.179
sure that, and it allows you to split up code in between cells where you might not

00:14:02.179 --> 00:14:06.099
usually be able to, and all kinds of other things, which I won't get into in this talk

00:14:06.099 --> 00:14:09.700
because fastcore is a completely different talk by itself, and it's very interesting

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:12.960
even on its own.

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:15.380
So you might be wondering, what does Quarto enable?

00:14:15.380 --> 00:14:17.460
So what does Quarto fit into this?

00:14:17.460 --> 00:14:19.059
So it's actually really exciting.

00:14:19.059 --> 00:14:24.299
Before Quarto, we had a different kind of fragmented system for, you know, we had a

00:14:24.299 --> 00:14:29.260
separate project for blogs, and a separate project for books, and a separate project

00:14:29.260 --> 00:14:32.900
for, you know, documentation.

00:14:32.900 --> 00:14:37.900
And then we were also trying to figure out, well, what if you want to document your existing

00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:40.020
code base that's not written in mbdev?

00:14:40.020 --> 00:14:42.059
Can you use mbdev?

00:14:42.059 --> 00:14:48.179
Because mbdev has a lot of nice sugar for documenting existing code bases as well.

00:14:48.179 --> 00:14:51.460
And so now we have a common framework for all of that.

00:14:51.460 --> 00:14:53.260
You don't have, you know, a common set of tools.

00:14:53.260 --> 00:14:56.780
No matter what kind of format you want to produce, you can use, you do that because

00:14:56.780 --> 00:14:57.780
of Quarto.

00:14:57.780 --> 00:15:03.380
It's also a very stable infrastructure, like, you know, we're very impressed by JJ and his

00:15:03.380 --> 00:15:04.820
support on this project.

00:15:04.820 --> 00:15:12.539
He's been amazing in kind of adding features, squashing bugs, you name it, it's been special.

00:15:12.539 --> 00:15:14.539
And we can also offload a lot of work.

00:15:14.539 --> 00:15:18.619
There's a lot of commonality between mbdev and Quarto, like a lot of directives that

00:15:18.619 --> 00:15:20.299
Quarto has.

00:15:21.140 --> 00:15:24.780
We don't have to do that anymore because Quarto is doing it.

00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:26.619
The notebook filters are great.

00:15:26.619 --> 00:15:33.500
You know, JJ added notebook filters, you know, in part for mbdev.

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:36.500
And that makes it very customizable.

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:41.580
You can do anything, essentially, with notebooks in that situation.

00:15:41.580 --> 00:15:44.940
And then also there's a flexibility to use any static site generator.

00:15:44.940 --> 00:15:48.659
So, people want to, you know, use their own static site generator, like Docusaurus or

00:15:48.739 --> 00:15:49.739
something like that.

00:15:49.739 --> 00:15:54.859
And you can do that with Quarto because Quarto is kind of like this Pandoc super processor

00:15:54.859 --> 00:16:02.299
where you can mutate anything and create anything, which is amazing.

00:16:02.299 --> 00:16:05.539
So last thing I want to say is give mbdev a try.

00:16:05.539 --> 00:16:06.539
This is mbdev's website.

00:16:06.539 --> 00:16:09.460
Let me, I just want to show you the website.

00:16:09.460 --> 00:16:14.359
The website is, the homepage for the website is actually made in a notebook.

00:16:14.359 --> 00:16:16.659
This is a Quarto page.

00:16:16.659 --> 00:16:17.659
So this is really cool.

00:16:17.659 --> 00:16:18.940
It's amazing.

00:16:18.940 --> 00:16:24.539
And this, if you go behind and look at this, this is a QMD file, surprisingly enough.

00:16:24.539 --> 00:16:32.859
And yeah, this page is generated in a notebook, which I think is super cool.

00:16:32.859 --> 00:16:38.500
So yeah, please get in touch with me if this is interesting to you.

00:16:38.500 --> 00:16:42.419
You know, I'd really like to talk to anyone who's interested in this, but yeah, thank

00:16:42.419 --> 00:16:43.419
you.

00:16:43.419 --> 00:16:44.419
Thank you.

00:16:44.419 --> 00:16:45.419
Thank you.

00:16:45.419 --> 00:16:45.419


